            {
               "text": "From **Formula 4**, we conclude that we can describe our position on a circle in the following ways:\n- **Line 1**: Point **P** is at a distance **x** from the origin **O** and at a distance **y** from that same origin **O**.\n- **Line 2**: The distance **x** corresponds to the length of leg **a**, which projects the hypotenuse **c** onto the horizontal, while the distance **y** corresponds to the length of leg **b**, which projects the hypotenuse **c** onto the vertical;\n- **Line 3**: The total length of the projections can be expressed using the radius **c**, which represents the distance from the origin, and the angle θ, which represents the opening of the radius from the horizontal in a counterclockwise direction. Thus, we have the horizontal path expressed as <b>x = a = c × cos (θ)</b>, while the path made vertically can be expressed as <b>y = b = c × sin (θ)</b>.\n\nwhile the path made vertically can be expressed as:",
